bug.short_desc: [project creation] Class Cast Exception

long_desc.thetext:
Opened for IBM:
In the Create Dynamic Web Project Wizard, Tomcat does not show up in the "Target Runtime" list even though it has been already defined in preferences (Server > Installed Runtime).
This was reproduced on an IBM RAD built on WTP.
Steps: ===== 1. Create an entry for Tomcat v5.x in Server > Installed Runtime preferences. 2. Open the create Dynamic Web Project wizard, in the "Target Runtime" list, Tomcat does not show up, only the WebSphere entries are there. 3. Select one of the Websphere runtimes. 4. Click on the "New" button beside the Target Runtime list and create another Tomcat runtime. 5. After creating the tomcat runtime in step 4, it still does not show up in the Target Runtime list. 6. Select <None> in the target runtime list, then repeat step 4. 7. Now the Target Runtime list will contain *all* your created Tomcat runtimes.

The scenario you described is working as designed, however, I came across the following class cast exception which should be fixed:
!ENTRY org.eclipse.ui 4 0 2006-08-07 17:25:42.678 !MESSAGE java.lang.String incompatible with org.eclipse.wst.common.project.facet.core.runtime.IRuntime !STACK 0 java.lang.ClassCastException: java.lang.String incompatible with org.eclipse.wst.common.project.facet.core.runtime.IRuntime at org.eclipse.wst.common.componentcore.datamodel.FacetProjectCreationDataModelProvider.propertySet(FacetProjectCreationDataModelProvider.java) at org.eclipse.jst.j2ee.project.facet.J2EEFacetProjectCreationDataModelProvider.propertySet(J2EEFacetProjectCreationDataModelProvider.java:102) at org.eclipse.jst.j2ee.internal.web.archive.operations.WebFacetProjectCreationDataModelProvider.propertySet(WebFacetProjectCreationDataModelProvider.java:59) at org.eclipse.wst.common.frameworks.internal.datamodel.DataModelImpl.internalSetProperty(DataModelImpl.java:182) at org.eclipse.wst.common.frameworks.internal.datamodel.DataModelImpl.setProperty(DataModelImpl.java:172) at org.eclipse.wst.common.frameworks.internal.datamodel.ui.DataModelSynchHelper.setProperty(DataModelSynchHelper.java:189) at org.eclipse.wst.common.frameworks.internal.datamodel.ui.DataModelSynchHelper$ComboListener.modifyText(DataModelSynchHelper.java:107) at org.eclipse.swt.widgets.TypedListener.handleEvent(TypedListener.java:196) at org.eclipse.swt.widgets.EventTable.sendEvent(EventTable.java:66) at org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Widget.sendEvent(Widget.java:928) at org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Widget.sendEvent(Widget.java:952) at org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Widget.sendEvent(Widget.java:933) at org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Combo.wmCommandChild(Combo.java:2203)
The cause of this exception is as follows: when the Combo is selected, the SynchHelper picks up the event (and then remembers it is handling this combo). Then it pushes the changes down to the model; the model reacts and in turn sends events over to the facets page, which react and preselects some extended facets, this event in turn is picked up by the wizard, which in turn updates the model with the newly selected facets and then notifies out that the Runtimes should be updated (and not show Apache). The problem is that since the synchHelper is already handling the combo which needs to be updated, it will immiediatly exit (if it didn't then there would be an infinite loop). Since the combo is not updated, if the user then selects the now invalid Apache entry, the above ClassCastException will result
Thus the fix is to add another listener to the combo to force the update of its items. Please see the attached patch.
Created an attachment (id=47492) Patch

I am having trouble recreating the ClassCastException. But even before this I have to ask why is the original defect description working as designed? This seems very odd. The Tomcat targets do not show up unless you select <None> and then create a New Tomcat server? How is it possible that this is working as designed? If I cancel out of the wizard then all of the runtimes show up. Why are they not showing up in the original case?

I know this behavior seems kind of wacky; I'm not in agreement with the way it behaves, but this is how the facets page works. In this particular scenario, if a server with advanced features is selected (e.g. WAS 6.1) the facets framework drives the automatic selection of its advanced features. Once these advanced features are selected, there is no way to unselect them except by selecting the <none> entry or going to the second page and deselecting them there. The runtimes list on the first page is supposed to be narrowed down as selection of facets on the second page are made (e.g. if you select a facet not supported by a runtime, then that runtime is supposed to be filtered out so the list of runtimes contains only those runtimes supporting all selected facets). There has been a lot of heated discusion on this topic in the past, and this is the agreed upon behavior.

Hey - This does sound very strange - I must be missing something.... I thought originally it was because add to ear was selected, and the tomcat server was filtered....
Now it sounds like when we select a specific servers that automatically presets specific server facets, we are locked in....
What was the argument for keeping the server list unfiltered? I would rather have that behavior, and if there is a warning/error with the settings, we show it... (for example selecting tomcat and add to ear). Then if we were able to select tomcat, a new set of presets would be set. The first page should always drive the second.... This is the 99% case....

I tried another fix which is to never filter the runtimes list; turns out it isn't quite that trivial because if no filtering is done, then a runtime like Tomcat would show up for a project like EJBs. Some basic filter needs to be done; perhaps based on the presets or the fixed facets; I will investigate further.
You are correct. Some basic filtering is required based on the project type. But the changing of the facets should not further filter the list.

Created an attachment (id=47727) Patch
This patch changes the runtime filtering to show all runtimes except runtimes not supporting a set of core facets. The core facets are defined as an internal Collection property called REQUIRED_FACETS_COLLECTION which is setup by all subclasses (each subclass decides what is a core facet).
Approve

While the scope of this patch was originally concerning, it is the same change repeated for each creation type.
Approve.
code checked in.

Talk about miscommunications! It appears that the solution that you guys iterated to is exactly the solution that we agreed to when the notion of the default facets was first implemented. Changes on the facets selection page were never supposed to affect the first page. Not sure how the communication broke down, but I am glad that things are now as they should be.

Btw, if you believed that the original behavior was as agreed upon in prior discussions, it was a little sneaky to implement this change without consulting with all the parties involved in the original decision. As it happened, the new behavior is actually what was originally agreed upon, so no harm done, but a little more openness would not hurt in the future.
*** Bug 143146 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

Now wizards have three things: 1. The project <template> facets (associated with each wizard) 2. some presets 3. REQUIRED_FACETS_COLLECTION
It seems to me "project <template> facets" is reasonable than REQUIRED_FACETS_COLLECTION.
We can define two WAR project wizards with different template facets. Thus they can filter out different runtimes (initially but never changed by 2nd page).

Jason,
Does REQUIRED_FACETS_COLLECTION draw its info from the template associated with the wizard? It should, if it doesn't, as it would get in the way of subclassing otherwise.

REQUIRED_FACETS_COLLECTION does not get the info from the template. The info is gathered from the various subclasses. The DataModels are not in the UI layer and thus can't get at the template info. This was the best we could do without doing a major overhaul.

If REQUIRED_FACETS_COLLECTION is used to filter server runtime,
BEA Portal Web Project Wizard would have tomcat in the combo.
That is, this is a regression from 1.0.x...
Verified 082806.

bug.short_desc: Recursive functions

long_desc.thetext:
IOCLHelper helper = HelperUtil.createOCLHelper(); helper.setContext(RoleprocessuserPackage.eINSTANCE.getRole()); helper.define("getSubroles(r : Role) : Bag(Role) = r.subrole->collect(x : Role | Bag{x,x} )"); ->This works<- but: helper.define("getSubroles(r : Role) : Bag(Role) = r.subrole->collect(x : Role | getSubroles(x) )"); ->does not work ->Exception in thread "main" ->org.eclipse.emf.ocl.helper.OCLParsingException: illegal operation ->signature: (getSubroles(Role))
I posted this in NEWSgroup and Christian W. Damus wrote:
This looks like a bug. The getSubroles call in the collect body resolves first against the iterator variable x, then against the context (self) type. If Role (type of x) is not the context type, then getSubroles should still resolve against the context (whatever it is). I suspect that the problem is that, when parsing the operation definition, getSubroles isn't yet available to the OCL parser because it's in the middle of defining. These recursive definitions need to be supported.
This isn't an enhancement. It's a bug in a supported capability (operation definitions in OCL are supposed to support recursion).

Created an attachment (id=48564) Patch
Also have a look to bug 154695
Created an attachment (id=49696) That patch works for me, but I think there should be done something in errorhandling

The J2SE 5.0 (bug 156361) and UML Metamodel support (bug 163808) enhancements will ensure recursive references (in the def: expression body) to the property/operation being defined are supported, as well as an undefinition API (which is used in the case of failure to parser the property/operation body).

The new org.eclipse.ocl.OCL parser API supports recursive definitions of operations and properties (where a property may be derived from the same property of a related object of the same kind). In the event that the operation body or property derivation cannot be parsed, the definition is not retained (i.e., a dud feature doesn't linger).

bug.short_desc: Facets properties page add/remove button is misleading

long_desc.thetext:
On the facet properties page in the properties of a dynamic Web project the Add/Remove Project Facets... is misleading. This button is not only used for adding ad removing facets but for editing (changing the version) of currently selected facets. I think this button should be named differently such as "Modify Project Facets". Better yet, the current preference page only shows the selected options. I'd prefer (and it will more closely follow Eclipse convention) for the facets preference page to actually be the component of the dialog that is displayed by selecting the Add/Remove Project Facets... button. This means that users can actually modify facets directly in the preference page.
I've cced Janet Mockler for help with any other UI consistency tips.

I can change the button label to read "Modify Project Facets". I agree that it is a better label. Regarding the suggestion of allowing the facets to be modified directly in the properties page, that is not possible as there is no way to show wizard pages that correspond to various facet actions directly in the context of the properties page.
Created an attachment (id=46897) Screenshot of facet preference page

I'm not sure what you mean be "that is not possible as there is no way to show wizard pages that correspond to various facet actions directly in the context of the properties page." If the only limitation is the reuse of the wizard page code I think the wizard page should be refactored to allow for its reuse or the preference page should just be made interactive like the properties page.

The facet author associates a sequence of 0 or more wizard pages with each facet action (such as install, uninstall, or version change). There needs to be a way to show those wizard pages when a user modifies the set of facets via this property page. As there is no way to show those wizard pages within a properties page, we launch a separate wizard.

Seems that none of the default facets make use of this feature. Do you have any idea about the number of facets that make use of this feature compared to the number that don't?
Do you think it will be too clumsy to provide an advanced button on the preference page for each facet that does provide a wizard page? Clicking the advanced button can then open the contributed wizard page.

Most facets utilize this only for install. The third page that you see in the Dynamic Web Project wizard is contributed by the jst.web facet. While wtp doesn't make heavy use of this, this is an important feature for downstream products / adopters.

To follow up on this, my original intention with this bug and what I want it to focus on is the Add/Remove button being renamed to Modify. This is an user experience enhancement. Given the simplicity of the change I'd prefer that we handle this in 1.5.1 unless there are translation requirements not to do so. (Jeff, please pipe in on the translation requirements if any.)
I will attach a patch with the suggested change.
Created an attachment (id=47260) Update for button label from Add/Remove to Modify

I suggest we stay with "Add/Remove" in 1.5.1. Since there will not be any translation cycle for 1.5.1, the "Modify" label will stay un-translated for non-English users. Although this will make English users' experience a lot better, it will not for non-English users (will probably make the non-English users' experience worse).
Jeff, as the string has already been translated as Add/Remove won't the experience be the same for non-English users? I see this fix, as you said, as having benefit for English users.
Since we are re-using the same properties key, there's no change to non-English users. Thanks for the clarification.
Any remaining objections to making this very safe fix that will benefit the English version of the project?

It seems that the bar is pretty low to non-existent for what goes into 1.5.1, which worries me a bit. Are we going to create a defacto 1.6 instead of a service pack? I would prefer if PMC better defined the parameters for allowable 1.5.1 fixes.

Kosta, I agree that we need to lock down 1.5.1. I think the changes I was suggesting for the facets properties page are certainly out of scope. Because of the simplicity of the Add/Remove to Modify change and the usability improvement for the English version I think this change is appropriate.

Lawrence, Kosta... I spoke with Kirk about this. He is the web tools usability guru... and he suggested this, and I agree with his reasoning:
"...I think I might have had a slight preference for keeping it as "Modify Project Facets". A single Modify button below a list usually indicates that you are going to modify the item selected in the list, which isn't the case here. "Modify Project Facets" might make it clearer that you're still dealing will all facets. In fact, if you want to add a new facet, it might not be clear how you can do that if you only see a Modify button that you think modifies existing facets... Modify Project Facets has a broader meaning. However, since the change has already been made, keeping it as Modify is probably OK... they'll click it once and see that it doesn't apply to the selected item."
(From update of attachment 47260) This change hasn't been made yet so based on Janet's latest post we should go with the initial patch.

Given Comment #17, is it actually better to leave the label as "Add/Remove Project Facets"? Yes "add/remove" doesn't cover all the actions that you perform in the resulting dialog, but perhaps it is a more obvious label for a novice users.

I read comment #17 as stating that the label "Modify Project Facets" should be clearer for users to understand that the button will allow you add, edit or remove existing facets. Janet, can you clarify Kirk's intention with his comment? Is it better to leave the button as "Add/Remove Project Facets" or change it to "Modify Project Facets"? Thanks.
My suggestion was "Modify Project Facets", rather than just "Modify". Sorry for the confusion.
I think we should go with the "Modify Project Facets" label for the button. Any objections?

I ran this by some folks at BEA. Here is one piece of feedback from Troy Beecroft (BEA Workshop PgM):
======
I read thru the thread. For me its a toss up. Modify Project Facets is more general than Add/Remove Project Facets and so fits the version-change-only scenario better. However, it also initially suggests that youd just be tweaking the attributes of facets already on the project, rather than adding/removing the facets, so its not so good a fit for that scenario.
As Kirk suggested though, whatever minor initial wrong impression is conveyed by the label will probably be quickly corrected once the dialog pops. Given that clicking the button is really the only thing you can do on the panel, I dont think theres much danger of people not clicking the button - whatever the label says.
(On a side note - it is slightly misleading that you can select items in the table gives the impression you can do something to them. Would be more clear that the button does not act on the selected element if selection was disabled in the table. You could even give the table a read-only appearance, since it effectively is read-only. FWIW.)
======
I am of a similar opinion. I don't have a strong preference one way or the other, but I tend to think that "Modify" is not an improvement over "Add/Remove". To me, "Add/Remove Project Facets" is a more obvious label for a novice user (add/remove is a vastly larger usecase than version change or other operations you can perform in the dialog), while there is danger in someone interpreting "Modify Project Facets" as affecting the configuration of facets currently installed (which you cannot do via this dialog).

Kosta, I'm not sure what you mean by "while there is danger in someone interpreting "Modify Project Facets" as affecting the configuration of facets currently installed (which you cannot do via this dialog)." As I understand the dialog the user can change the configuration or facets installed for the project. Is that not correct?
Perhaps a compromise and better solution is to combine the two suggestions into "Add/Modify/Remove Project Facets". Is this just a ridiculously long label for a button?

No, the dialog does not provide a way to modify configurations of facets currently installed (unless you are referring to the version number). Once a facet is installed, it is configured via project property pages or other mechanisms supplied by the facet's author.
Here is the list of things that the user can do in that dialog:
1. install a facet 2. uninstall a facet 3. change facet version 4. change the set of runtimes that the project is targetting 5. change the designated primary runtime
I almost think that "Modify" is a better label than "Modify Project Facets" as it is vague about exactly what you would be modifying (doesn't imply anythin it shouldn't). The issue that Kirk brought up can potentially be aleviated by inserting an explanatory label underneath the list and above the button that would say something like "To add or remove project facets, change the facet version, or to modify the runtimes that the project is targetting, select the Modify button". I am sure someone could come up with better wording that avoids the "click here" anti-pattern.
Janet, comments? Is the descriptive approach Kosta proposes used in Eclipse?

I like the idea of making the list of facets unselectable/read-only. In which case I would be fine with just Modify or Modify Facets. But I think either is fine. (I don't know if a description is really needed here... I think it's not too hard to discover what you can do from the dialog. Janet is on vacation btw).

Typically a button should be self explanatory. However if an explanations is needed, then this can sometimes be found under the main content page label.
If an item in a list is read-only, then the text should be a medium colour of grey to indicate that its not editable and/or when its selected the "Modify..." button should be disabled.

Just to be clear, the above (about disabling the Modify button) is true of some of the items in the list are editable but some are not. In this case, none of the items in the list are ever editable (in the sense that you can select one and edit just that one). More specifically, selecting an item in the list of facets has absolutely no meaning in this case... it does not affect the behavior of the Modify button (which brings up a dialog where you can choose which items to edit). So it may make sense to show the list as read-only, but we don't want to disable the Modify button.

Following on my comment #22, there have been no objections to labeling the button "Modify Project Facets".
Kosta, are you good to commit this change for 1.5.1?

I would prefer to not attempt this for 1.5.x. I made an inventory of other places that the "Add/Remove" term is used and there are two additional places in the UI as well as one place in the API. I would prefer to postpone this until 2.0 when we have more time and flexibility to craft an appropriate solution.

The link on the Targeted Runtimes property page that opens the modify faceted project wizard is now "Uninstall Facets..." which makes sense in that context. 4. And with the potential planned changes in the launchers design (like moving startup.jar to a bundle) that would make a lot of sense.
Philippe is this still an issue for you? The launchers are now in the org.eclipse.equinox.executable feature as part of the launcher rework.

All the needed files for the application should be in plug-ins (OSGI bundles), not in the feature that may not be shipped with a product... AFAIK this is the only exception now in *all* of Eclipse products, this should probably be fixed.
With p2 comming up this makes even more sense.
moving to equinox

bug.short_desc: Support patch fragments

long_desc.thetext:
Jeff reminded everyone of the package expert guidelines for the platform: http://dev.eclipse.org/mhonarc/lists/eclipse-dev/msg07550.html
Jeff said: "As we have seen in the past couple days, the community's desire/need for the freedom to access non-API is overwhelming. In fact, this forms a critical part of the Eclipse ecosystem allowing experimentation and investigation. This approach is NOT at odds with, and is fundamentally separate from, our ongoing work to get control over the API and help developers stay on "the right path". "
I think this could go even a bit further to foster experimentations.
Why not making every platform bundle extensible using the fragment classpath trick?
Making every bundles have the following manifest entry (or update it if it already exists) would make extending the platform in an orderly way possible with a fragment that would provide an eclipse-extensions.jar to the bundle host it wants to extend or patch:
Bundle-ClassPath: eclipse-extensions.jar, .
I think it is in the same spirit as Jeff's email and goes a long way to support clean and orderly community API experimentations.
There are probably tons of objections, but IMHO the benefits outweight any of them.

> There are probably tons of objections
One downside: this would allow arbitrary third parties to spoof/hijack any class in your bundle. I know this is your goal, but it doesn't seem like a step in the right direction from a security point of view.

(In reply to comment #1) > > There are probably tons of objections > > One downside: this would allow arbitrary third parties to spoof/hijack any > class in your bundle. I know this is your goal, but it doesn't seem > like a step in the right direction from a security point of view.
John: Agreed, but this is another problem, which should be addressed separately, IMHO. The platform is not a secured and trusted enviroment. Providing for extensibility does not make the platform any less secure than before. Making it a tad harder to modify the platform - the way it is today - does not make the platform more or less secure. Or else the whole plugin idea is just a big security gap.
In the case of the suggested feature, it already exists for the workbench. The only instances I have seen of folks using that feature was to provide interesting patches released with all the caveats needed, like the workbench splitter, and it may be used too for necessary enhancements to products built on eclipse. So if there was a security issue, then it is already in anyway.
And you know better than me that there are tons of other ways to spoof/hijack the platform code already available for someone who would want to.
For instance, it may be much easier to distribute a patched bundle in the platform namespace with a new version. That patched plugin could even hide itself under another jar file name, and still override any of the platform provided classes, afaik. That would make the version resolution and the OSGi bundle loading mechanism a security risks too since it allows the installation of a new bundle. And the whole dynamic bundle story is security risk too in that context. I can write code that downloads and installs a dynamic bundle with a higher version at runtime and none could notice.
So as much as a small part of me accepts the security objection, I would personally leave security issues in their own realm, where they can be addressed with the right mechanisms, whatever that can be like a run mode of eclipse which would "secured" working in the context of security manager and adequate policies which could prohibit using that type of fragments, which could disable dynamic bundle invocations, authorize only a safe and signed list of bundles/versions to run and so on. Things that the Higgins project probaly cares for.
What do you think?

I agree with John that this will be a move in a wrong direction.
Should Eclipse implement the classpath trick, it would have to be supported in future. Meaning that this will be a security hole (and a rather big one :-)) that would have to be maintained for backward compatibility.
Even taking security question aside, this approach is quite questionable. The reason is obvious: the non-API code can change at any time. In this case you are not only calling non-API methods, but replacing parts of the functionality. What are the chances that code you replacing is going to work the same way in the next release? Even if it is not modified in a significant way, how about bug fixes incorporated in the new versions?
Much more practical way would be to submit a patch, and, while it is not being released, just modify the target plugins you use in the development environment with the same patch.
As for the quote from the newsgroup, IMHO, there is a big difference between experimenting with non-API calls during the development cycle and releasing a product that depends on replacing *parts* of internal processing that weren't intended to be replaced.
fair enough!

There actually is a need for this kind of behaviour. We have talked about it in the past as "patch fragments". Fragments whose classpath goes on the hosts classpath first. The focus of that work was somewhat different from the original post here. We were looking more at product scenarios where there may be a need to patch a deployed product. We imagined ways of controling the mechanism by, for example, ensuring that the patch fragment was signed by the same signer as the host.
I'm going to reopen this for now. I suspect we have a bug about patch fragments but I can't find it right now.

bug.short_desc: Binary Search Thread doesn't scale

long_desc.thetext:
Time to get this into the books.
I'm working with ACE+TAO which produces a large number of binaries when you build the whole thing. On startup, the binary parser can take a lot of time, especially when shutdowns aren't clean.
There have been a lot of reports of the binary parser getting in the way of workflows. It's time to evaluate what we are trying to accomplish with this and maybe find a way so that the binary parser only runs when information is requested.

(In reply to comment #0) > Time to get this into the books. > I'm working with ACE+TAO which produces a large number of binaries when you > build the whole thing. On startup, the binary parser can take a lot of time, > especially when shutdowns aren't clean.
Sure it may take sometimes to go through the files, but you still can work without being affected?
> There have been a lot of reports of the binary parser getting in the way of > workflows.
Ho? I am a little suprise, I just fix the head to decrease the priority can you try this when you have a chance?
> It's time to evaluate what we are trying to accomplish with this and > maybe find a way so that the binary parser only runs when information is > requested.
This is a convenient framework for many things, you can restrict where the binary parser will run ... but unfortunately it is not well integrated to the builders.
But please give the head a go and let us if know if it is still a problem, running a background thread should not disrupt the workflow.

I have added a content type called binaryFile which is a super type for the binary content types provided by managed build. The binary parser now only runs if a file has no extension, the extension is a number which is common for versioned shared libraries, or the file has the binaryFile content type.
The binaries search for Firefox now finishes in a few seconds, compared to over a minute previously.

We don't build the binaries inside the workspace anyway so the only resources we want the binary search thread to visit are the imported executables at the root of the project. We need a way to limit the level the search thread visits.

(In reply to comment #3) > We don't build the binaries inside the workspace anyway so the only resources > we want the binary search thread to visit are the imported executables at the > root of the project. We need a way to limit the level the search thread visits.
I believe it also only checks output folders which I also believe support exclusions. If that's not working then we need to fix output folders too. Please raise a separate bug for that.
The good news is that the binary parser did all of Firefox in about 3 seconds.

bug.short_desc: [launcher] Setting -classpath when launching via eclipse.exe

long_desc.thetext:
When developing RCP applications youn can start your App within eclipse and set a bootstrap entry which is appended to -cp when the application is launched.
If you now export your Application you cannot pass the additional classpath because eclipse.exe starts up with java -jar startup.jar -os .... .
Why couldn't eclipse simply start using java -classpath startup.jar org.eclipse.core.launcher.Main -os ... and append all parameters passed via -vmargs -classpath My.jar ?
Am I missing something really obvious?

We will have to wait for Pascal to comment. I think the -jar option was used to prevent the CLASSPATH environment variable from being used. On systems where this was defined extra jars would be stuck onto the classpath that would cause issues in Eclipse.

-jar was introduced to give more flexibility to people willing to use another startup.jar and since the content of classpath is never used by eclipse this was not seen as a limitation. Currently I think you can work around this problem by using the "download extensions" markup from the manifest.mf. See http://java.sun.com/developer/Books/javaprogramming/JAR/basics/manifest.html#download
Stuff you place on the application classpath is not available to bundle classloaders by default. By design eclipse isolates bundles from the application classloader.

I may miss something here, but it seems to me that this is the design point of the short circuit boolean operators in the Java language (same as C and C++ for that matter).
While a | b will evaluate a, then b, and return true if any of these be true, a || b will evaluate a, then return true if it's true, else evaluate b and return its value. Hence, if the line boolean b = maybeAdd(p1, q, range) results into b being true, the line b = b || maybeAdd(p2, q, range) will by the language spec not call maybeAdd(p2, q, range).
If you want to make sure both get called, please consider using the ordinary or operator, that is '|'.

For now I'm tempted to keep with the eclipse.org convention that everything in the editor does not take effect until it is 'saved', which in our case is a combo of save and submit (e.g. direct actions can only be done via the task list or via a wizard, which is in line with conventions). It may also make sense to add an "Obsolete" column with checkboxes that user can uncheck to mark attachments obsolete...

I've implemented everything to be generic in the tasks namespace so far, maybe this should be bugzilla specific? The RepositoryAttachment class has an isObsolete() method so it seems the concept of obsolete attachments is generic to all repo types, perhaps an obsoleteAttachment() method should be added to the IAttachmentHandler instead of making this bugzilla specific.
thoughts?
Since other attributes may change, perhaps we need a more generic method like updateAttachment(...)? That way we don't have methods for each attribute that may change.

In fact, there may be other capabilities who are applicable to bugzilla but not in other connector(s), and vice-versa.
The problem here is to define a stable interface not tied to any specific repository connector.
I didn't take a look on the connector architecture used in Mylar, but I presume it is actually based on a interface hierarchy implemented by concrete connectors.
Have you considered adopting a adapter-based architecture like in ECF Container's model?
This way there can be a number of interfaces defining "capabilities" that a connector can have, and each connector implements the interfaces for the capabilities it supports.
In this model, if you want to know if a connector X supports a capability Y, all you have to do is ask it for the corresponding interface via IAdapterManager.
Of course, maybe this can be a complex solution to this specific issue, but it is something that we can face when considering how to evolve the connector architecture in a flexible way.
Just my 0,02 cents...

bug.short_desc: Local history lost when reverting file

long_desc.thetext:

The version control I use is Subversion with Subclipse 1.0.3 plugin.

The local history covers any state of the file that is written to disk. If you are working in an editor, that buffer is never written to disk until the editor is saved, so local history does not apply. However, if you accidentally revert the editor, then Edit -> Undo will undo the revert and get you back to the previous state. The editor's undo buffer acts like a limited local history within the context of an unsaved editor.

Let's me try to re-elaborate my issue again. As I think my initial explanation is quite ambigious.
When doing a Team Revert (revert to lastest prestine version in a SCS), the Local History should keep the changes made and saved. However, it turns out that when doing a Team Revert, the Local History for changes during the period is completely lost.
Here is the scenario, using Subclipse for Subversion SCS. * Update the workspace to latest version. * Edit a file and save. At this point Local History will contains the change I just made. * Do Team > Revert on the file. The file is reverted to latest prestine version. And Local History is lost, too. There is no possible way to recover back the change I made.
Local History should not be lost as a consequence of Team Revert because this is what Local History is used for, to keep a local history of files.

Ah, I didn't realize you were talking about a team operation. This is a bug in Subclipse. In their implementation of Team Revert, they need to specify the KEEP_HISTORY flag when they call IResource.setContents() to request that a local copy be held in the local history. I suggest reporting this to the maintainers of Subclipse.

When Subclipse does a revert we are running a Subversion API which restores the file to its pristine content. We are not doing anything within Eclipse or on the IResource. We do send a resource change notification so that the status of the resource would be refreshed.
What would cause Eclipse to remove all of the history? Does it see that the file contents now match the original so it destroys the history that was created.

Ok, that makes sense. Since Subversion is going directly to the file system, and Eclipse only finds out about the change after the fact, there's no opportunity to save the old file contents in the local history. Only changes made using the Eclipse API can be saved in the local history (because we need to know about the change before it happens so we have access to the old contents).

John, I think that is not the problem. Maybe I just read the bug wrong but to me it sounds Eclipse looses the already existing file history of a file that is changed outside of Eclipse. Shouldn't Eclipse at least keep the already existing file history?

I played with this last week, and I am not sure what the original poster is saying is correct. I can make changes save, make changes save etc.. Then do a revert. If I then do Compare with -> Local History I can see those changes.
Perhaps only the last change is lost because of the reason John gave? So maybe if you only made one change, "all history" is lost?
I also got the impression that one of the views that shows history was perhaps filtering out items that did not show differences (or something of that nature). Because if I then made additional edits to the file, I would see some history entries I was not seeing before.
John, is there some API we could call prior to running Subversion's revert that would allow the History processing to run?
Vairoj, is *all* the local history missing for the file, or just the state of the file immediately before the revert is done?

From further experimenting, it looks like only the state of the file immediately before the revert is lost.
Therefore, if only one change is made, all the history will be lost. If there are several changes, only the last change will be lost.

I do not quite understand that why this should be the expected behavior. In my opinion, Local History is the feature I am counting on when there is a mistake. And in this case, some times I mistakenly revert the file. If Local History do keep the last change, I can recover from the mistake.

My "expected behaviour" comment was about the behaviour of the Eclipse API, not about the expected behaviour from the end-user's point of view. From the view of the Eclipse API, Eclipse is not aware of the "revert" operation until it is completed, at which point it cannot store the previous version in the local history. I agree the expected behaviour from the end user's point of view is that the state prior to the revert would appear in local history, but this is a problem in the subclipse plugin.

bug.short_desc: Target runtime ... is not defined

long_desc.thetext:
I moved a project out of one workspace and into a new directory. Then I switched workspace, using this new directory, and imported the project as "existing project". But I cannot build because of an error I cannot solve: Target runtime Apache TGomcat v5.5 is not defined. What to do?
The closest I found was under Project->Properties->Server where there is another mysterious message: (sure wish I could copy the text from these pages!) "Set the default server used by Run on Server for this project. To change the server runtime targetted by this project go the the Projects Facets page." Well there is no "Facets" under Projects. I don't know if this is connected with the other problem, but now I can't build my project.

More info...I started looking for other stuff I didn't understand. I deleted a directory called ".settings" under my project folder which contained stuff I didn't create. Bingo! The build completes.
I still have two weird warnings:
Implementation of project facet jst.java could not be found. Functionality will be limited. wvn Unknown 1154064243375 355
Implementation of project facet jst.web could not be found. Functionality will be limited. wvn Unknown 1154064243375 356
Sadly this kind of mystery stuff now weighs on eclipse.
Questions like this should be asked on the newsgroup first. http://www.eclipse.org/newsgroups/

Created an attachment (id=46952) Properties->Server with no runtime options and ref to missing facets
This popup illustrates that my Server dialog is missing runtime options and has a text reference to an Eclipse menu item that does not exits (Project Facet).

Sorry I do not agree. There are four bugs here:
1) The error message "Target runtime... is not defined" should be hyperlinked to the origin of the problem so that new users have a reasonable chance to fix it and experienced users have a quick way to fix it. This "everything linked back" must be a Golden Rule of IDEs like Eclipse because the old method of mapping errors to sources has been broken when the command sequence (build.xml or Makefile) was taken over by the IDEs internal logic. That is, formerly I could know where to look for the problem by observing where in the command sequence the error emerged. Eclipse doesn't reveal this sequence does it?
2) The documented way to set the target runtime is given in http://www.eclipse.org/webtools/community/tutorials/BuildJ2EEWebApp/BuildJ2EEWebApp.html via a panel Projects->Properties->Server which has runtime choices. However my copy of Projects->Properties->Server has no choices. I have attached a JPEG to illustrate this.
3) The Projects->Properties->Server dialog references an Eclipse menu item (I guess, it is vague) called "Project Facet" that does not exist in my environment. The dialog should link the Project Facet page rather than have me hunt for it; finding that I don't have such a page the dialog should tell me how to get it or at least what it is.
4) If the IDE imports a project it should analyze all of the configuration information to verify that the state of the IDE can support the configuration. Specifically in this case the IDE should have rejected my .settings file if it could not understand it, ideally offering to delete and reconstruct it. Since this file is not user created it is up to the IDE to maintain its consistency.

Hi John,
1. The error message is coming from the platform, not WTP. It occurs because in your old workspace you were targeting (building against) the Tomcat runtime that you had defined, but it doesn't exist in the new workspace. If you defined a new Tomcat runtime in the new workspace with the same name "Apache Tomcat v5.5" the error would go away. I can look at adding a quick fix to resolve this problem (it would probably just open the Server > Installed Runtimes preferences page for you) but that's a (valid) new feature request.
2. The reason you don't see the other options is because of comment #1. The .settings folder includes information relating to facets and the J2EE structure of the project. Your project is now missing several bits of vital information, so that's why the pages aren't showing up. (for instance, you've probably deleted the bit that tells the IDE that this is a web project) You can contact the jst.j2ee team or try to recreate those resources, but if that's not possible you'll need to create a new project and move the resources over.
3. Normally the two pages are literally next to each other so I hadn't gotten around to putting in the link. However, since the Server page can be visible when the other ones aren't (e.g. in the case of a corrupt project), I'll just use this bug to remove the reference.
4. The original error message you received had nothing to do with .settings. The files in this directory are 'owned' by several different teams, so if you want to pursue this then I'd suggest starting by opening a new bug or transferring this one to jst.j2ee.

Hi John,
As above, here the state of the problems you listed:
1. Standard Eclipse behaviour with possible feature request for a quick fix to help with the resolution.
2. Caused by user error.
3. Fixed in WTP 1.5.1.
4. Caused by other WTP components.
Do you want to use this bug for the quick fix feature request, do you want to transfer it on to components like jst.j2ee for looking at #4, or is there anything I'm missing?

I think #1 (lack of information to know what IDE action causes an error message) is a pervasive problem so acting on #4 (analyzing imported projects for consistency) makes more sense. Can you do what is needed?
Regarding #2 I'm not sure how users would avoid the problems I encountered. Nothing marks the project as "only valid for J2EE", so what advice would I give someone to avoid my error? Other than tne not-very-helpful "Don't import projects in to eclipse".

That's likely to be the problem. In the current version, TPTP does not check that the remote platform has all the plugins available. The list of plugins to activate can be edited in the workbench location editor (in the "Eclipse Workbench Properties" tab > "Choose plug-ins to launch from the list"). You need to uncheck in this list all the plug-ins that are not installed on your remote eclipse. Also, you need to make sure that the versions of the plug-ins shown in this list match the versions of the plug-ins on the remote machine (the versions need to be *completely* identical). > > Also, the Location text box on the local eclipse is not the same as the remote > one. If you mean the "Eclipse location" text box, this field must contain the path of the eclipse directory on the remote machine.
